******
[2]
Date: Mon 31 Jan 2022
Source: Antara News [in Indonesian, machine trans., edited]
https://www.antaranews.com/berita/2676181/bbvet-wates-rekomendasikan-pemkab-gunung-kidul-tidak-keluarkan-ternak


The Wates Veterinary Center recommends that the Government of Gunung Kidul Regency, Yogyakarta Special Region, does not remove livestock from the anthrax spreading location in Gedangsari and Ponjong Districts to prevent the spread of anthrax.

The Head of the Wates Veterinary Center Hendra Wibawa in Gunung Kidul said on [Mon 31 Jan 2022] that, based on the results of the BBVet Wates investigation with the Livestock and Health Service of Gunung Kidul in the 2 sub-districts, 11 cows and 4 goats were found to be positive for anthrax bacteria. "To prevent the spread of anthrax bacteria, we recommend that the district government should not remove cows or other livestock from the area until control is complete. Then, it is necessary to accelerate treatment of livestock and vaccinations in and around the spread of anthrax," said Hendra.

In addition, BBVet Wates recommends that the Gunung Kidul Regency Government tighten the entry and exit of livestock in the anthrax distribution area so that it is easy to control. "There needs to be strict supervision of animals that come out and enter Gunung Kidul, especially at the location where anthrax is spreading," he said.

According to Hendra, animals affected by anthrax can be cured if handled quickly, starting from administering drugs and administering vaccinations. Healing takes 3 to 4 weeks provided treatment is done quickly. "Treatment and vaccination, as well as rapid treatment can control the spread of anthrax bacteria," he said.

He also admitted that indications of the spread of anthrax bacteria in Gunung Kidul occurred in mid-December [2021], but BBVet Wates received a report in January [2022]. After receiving the report, BBVet Wates and the Gunung Kidul Livestock and Animal Health Service conducted an investigation. "Until now there has been no increase in livestock deaths, because the Livestock and Animal Health Service has moved quickly to avoid spread of the anthrax bacteria," he said.

Meanwhile, the Regent of Gunung Kidul, Sunaryanta, admitted that there were findings of animals exposed to anthrax bacteria. However, there are no people who are positive for anthrax from laboratory results. "People have indications of being exposed to anthrax bacteria, but no one has medically stated that condition. We'll just have to wait," he said.

