[Yogyakarta in is the middle of the southern coast of Java, Indonesia; see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yogyakarta. For a map of the province, see https://whereismap.net/where-is-yogyakarta-located-what-country-is-yogyakarta-in-yogyakarta-map/.

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Yogyakarta, Special Region of Yogyakarta, Indonesia: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6900392,27938.

Many thanks to Mahmoud for sending us these reports.

Anthrax can be difficult to diagnose in humans although it is very easy in animals -- for starters, swab the nasal turbinates. My good friend, Benyamin Cherkaskyi, who had a wealth of Soviet experience with this disease, told me that the best samples to take from humans was of the bloody fluid under the cutaneous lesion, similarly from the thoracic and abdominal cavities if it has spread there. Added to the problems of human diagnosis is their habit of self-treating with antibiotics before they see a doctor. _B. anthracis_ is normally very sensitive to antibiotics and you can culture nothing from the toxins.

Cattle will die from acute infections, and their carcasses usually initiate calls for veterinary help. But among the other animals still standing one will find animals with a temperature -- feeling with one's hand is usually sufficient -- and maybe on the edge of dying. Treated promptly with antibiotics they can be pulled back from death. Others may just be incubating an infection, and thus a benefit of treating with long-acting antibiotics. Among my veterinary field colleagues, there was a bit of a controversy about simultaneously vaccinating and antibiotic treatment. Both claimed success. I think that the reason for this is that the vaccine dose is large enough for a significant number of Sterne spores germinating after the antibiotic titer had fallen away.

Any herd subjected to an outbreak of anthrax should be vaccinated annually for up to 5 years to stop recurrences and neighboring herds should also be similarly vaccinated. Judging when an area is free of risk depends on the knowledge of the local livestock owners. At some point, one will stop vaccinating but it is vitally important for all to be aware of any unsuspected death, which must be called in and investigated. These usually are anthrax cases in unvaccinated animals, and thus the need to continue vaccinating for say 3 years. Effective control is usually some 8 years and then followed by active surveillance to confirm eradication. Whatever the textbooks say, this is an eradicable disease.

Not mentioned in this veterinary report was the disposal of anthrax carcasses, although obviously some were home butchered and the meat sold or given away. Carcasses, if possible, should be burnt and any bloody soil treated with disinfectant, the stronger the better. - Mod.MHJ

